{"key":"processedPost-13167271","value":{"id":13167271,"first":13164584,"last":13169087,"when":1283995623,"utime":"09/09/10 04:27 AM","content":"You don't need to dissolve the gypsum.&nbsp; Simply mix it in with the substrate.&nbsp; The mycelium will get what it needs.&nbsp; After all, mycelium can munch down vermiculite, so gypsum is no problem either.&nbsp; I mix the gypsum in with dry substrate ingredients, and then add moisture to the proper level.&nbsp; There also is no 'recipe'.&nbsp; Simply mix what you have in whatever quantities you have them.&nbsp; A mixed substrate is superior to a single-ingredient substrate, thus if you mix horse or cow manure, coir, vermiculite, straw, etc., the results will be superior to any one by itself.<br />RR","title":"Re: Coir Recipe"}}